Well...anyway...<br>
<br>
This is mainly to you, Silverblade, in response to the following comments you've made in this socio-economic debate, but this is also to all those other people that jumped on the Capitalist/anti-Socialist bandwagon without fully developing their thoughts out.... At least Silverblade made a concise (though angry) arguement for his position<br>
<br>
Before I say my piece, I want to make a few things clear. First of all, I am a Chinese American. Second, my family fled China after the Communists took over. Third, I have excellent reason to believe that the rest of my family was slaughtered as my Grandfather held an official diplomatic position within a Chinese embassy under the Republic and came to America instead of answering the Communist-ordered recall.... that, and the fact that my Uncle, who later escaped to America, confirmed this...<br>
<br>
So, it is understanble to assume that my following comments are made because of personal bias.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> <br>
<br>
*SOCIALISM* is the idea of &quot;people come first, peopel are important&quot;, it's NOT freakin' communism, are you dense? Problem is that folk take it as a &quot;political absolute&quot; rather than a basis for starting things from. or get so wrapped up in the beaurcracy of it they over look the fact that its about HUMAN BEINGS, be they one, or a million, ALL have rights<br>
<br>
Socialism is an IDEAL, so of course it don't work in this world because too many folk are pragmatic selfish bastrds.<br>
<br>
Ok, the basic problem with Capitlism is, that rather than seeing Capitolism as a methods of creating, and spreading wealth, therebye bettering everyone, it is in practice all about GREED and POWER.<br>
<br>
My gripe is with the constant harping that CAPITOLISM is &quot;good&quot; and the only method that works, and removing many safeguards and controls on corporations and financial institutions.<br>
ie Capitolism is being portrayed as &quot;&gt; democracy and socialism.&quot;, and being more important than governments and justice.<br>
<br>
Capitolism as merely a method of enriching folk's lives is good, as the moral structure and guiding light of your society it f**** sucks <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Please correct me if I'm wrong, but I believe that the above quotes basically sum up your posisition on this thread... I'm gonna divide this into answering your thoughts on Socialism and then your thoughts on Capitalism<br>
<br>
The textbook definition of Socialism has traditionally been that of a system of social government in which the means of production and distribution of goods are owned and controlled collectively or by the government. Now, the ideal behind this is economic and/or social equality, or in the very least, a lessening of of inequality, which is why production and control is centered in the government. <br>
<br>
In fulfilling this ideal, Socialism actually succeeds.<br>
<br>
The Soviet Union actually acomplished much during its 80 year rule. In a country with a history of backwardness, reactionism, and extreme social and economic inequity (thats the Russian Empire of the late 17th century to 1917 for you non history buffs), the Soviet government made huge strides. Almost overnight, Russia saw universal enfranchisement (that means everyone could vote for anything that was allowed to be voted for), equality between the sexes, universal health and medical care, and zero percent unemployment. <br>
<br>
Prior to 1917, Russia was primarily an agrarian economy with a laughable industrial economy. The saying goes that in World War I there were four men to a single rifle. <br>
<br>
By 1943, the Soviet Union actually outstripped the Nazi Germany in industrial productivity in the production of arms, armor, munitinos, cars, and steel by a large margin. <br>
<br>
An arguement could be made that the above statement is the work of Soviet propeganda and thus, not credible. However, this particualar statistic was NOT released by the Soviet Union, rather, it is the work of an American committe finding during the 50s that attempted to assess the military capability of the Soviets should America go to war with them.<br>
<br>
Thus, we can't simply say that the Soviet Union failed because none of it worked. Obviously, in regard to some areas, Socialism did a marvelous job of quickly bringing Russia into the modern world. <br>
<br>
So why did the Soviet Union in the long run fail? You yourself stated the reason Silverblade, albeit in a much more pessimistic way then I would have put it. Indeed, people on average are self-motivated and greedy. A correlation to this is that for a person, the desire to work hard and his/her personal advancement are in direct proportion. <br>
<br>
The ideal Socialistic society creates an enviroment where EVERYONE is equal, regardless of birth, sex, ACOMPLISHMENT, or EDUCATION.<br>
<br>
I stress these last two factors because they are why Socialism cannot work and why it does not work in the real world. Because everyone is equal regardless of who they are and what they do, there is no motivation (satistfaction of greed) for a person to achieve and personally advance within society because there is none. Personal advancement equates to social ineqality (if one person moves up a ladder to the next tier, where does that leave everyone else who didn't move up that ladder?). Once again, I go back to the Soviet Union for my example. <br>
<br>
During the second Five Year Plan under the Stalinist regime, a system of quotas was developed for factories. To make this discussion empirically manageble, lets assume that the factories were ordered to make 50 million nails per month. <br>
<br>
The result of this was that the Soviet Goverment recieved 50 million tiny half cenimeter nails that were brittle (because of their small size) and generally useless. That month, 50 million nails were melted down resulting in a loss in productivity.<br>
<br>
The second month, the Soviet government changed the quotas from amount of nails to tonnage, they instead asked for 200 tons of nails (i have no idea how much nails weigh). What resulted was the production of about a hundred huge nails, each weighing 2 tons. Once again, due to the inherent lazyness of people, production fell off. <br>
<br>
While the above example may seem idiotic, it actually did happen. (The foremen and several of the workers were subsequently shot as &quot;slackers&quot; and &quot;enemies of the people&quot; after that, the factory met the next month's quotas adequetely and according to standards).<br>
<br>
Another, more recent example is the fact that in 1991, when the Soviet Union collapsed, there was one brand of toothpaste availble to the public in the country..(and it tasted horrible, believe me).<br>
<br>
Socialism, is inherently flawed due to the fact that unless Civil Rights are violated, there is no motivation for people to work hard and achieve. Thus, on average, while productivity as a whole increases, quality of products suffers because there is no motivation to maintain quality, only quotas to keep. It is all Civil Rights violations can do to ensure that the quality of the production is even marginally acceptable. Also, because production is controlled by the government, there is an emphasis placed on &quot;guns&quot; (non-comsumer goods) rather than &quot;butter&quot; (consumer goods) which leads to a generally less standard of living for the populace.<br>
<br>
Conclusion: While everyone is indeed equal in Socialism, while everyone is equally treated, and while everyone equally matters, they are equally poor, equally hungry, and generally equally less well off. Silverblade, in light of this, when the core theory is so very much flawed (as opposed to slightly flawed which is Capitalism..and the next post), I can't see how one can make it the &quot;basis for starting things from&quot; without changing the fundemental concept of Socialism which is universal equality. <br>
<br>
edit:<br>
